1
00:01:02,195 --> 00:01:04,493
Honey, have you seen my wallet?

2
00:01:05,799 --> 00:01:08,200
Isn't it on the bedside table?

3
00:01:14,741 --> 00:01:17,267
Now, listen, we're running a little late.

4
00:01:17,477 --> 00:01:18,501
I know.

5
00:01:19,212 --> 00:01:20,611
How do I look?

6
00:01:20,814 --> 00:01:22,282
Perfect.

7
00:01:22,516 --> 00:01:24,177
Is my hair okay?

8
00:01:24,651 --> 00:01:25,812
It's great.

9
00:01:26,019 --> 00:01:28,078
You're not even looking at it.

10
00:01:29,289 --> 00:01:30,723
It's beautiful.

11
00:01:31,191 --> 00:01:32,920
You always look beautiful.

12
00:01:33,360 --> 00:01:35,454
Did you give Roz
the phone and pager numbers?

13
00:01:35,662 --> 00:01:38,131
Yeah, I put it on the fridge.
Let's go.

14
00:01:38,332 --> 00:01:39,332
Coming.

15
00:01:40,233 --> 00:01:41,758
All right.

16
00:01:42,002 --> 00:01:43,265
I'm ready.

17
00:02:00,287 --> 00:02:01,982
What's the babysitter's name?

18
00:02:02,189 --> 00:02:03,189
Roz.

19
00:02:05,692 --> 00:02:08,525
Okay, Roz, we're going now.

20
00:02:09,096 --> 00:02:11,588
You look amazing, Mrs. Harford.

21
00:02:11,798 --> 00:02:14,130
Thank you.
Helena, are you ready for bed?

22
00:02:14,334 --> 00:02:16,962
Yes, Mommy. Can I stay up
and watch <i>The Nutcracker</i>?

23
00:02:17,170 --> 00:02:19,070
- What time's it on?
- 9:00.

24
00:02:19,272 --> 00:02:22,034
- You can watch that.
- Can I stay up until you get home?

25
00:02:22,142 --> 00:02:25,203
- No, darling.
- It'll be a little late for that.

26
00:02:25,412 --> 00:02:27,676
The phone number is on the fridge,

27
00:02:27,881 --> 00:02:30,543
and there's food in there,
so help yourself.

28
00:02:30,751 --> 00:02:32,515
We shouldn't be later than 1:00.

29
00:02:32,719 --> 00:02:35,416
- I'll hold our cab to take you home.
- Thanks, Dr. Harford.

30
00:02:35,622 --> 00:02:36,987
You be good, baby.

31
00:02:37,891 --> 00:02:40,622
- Good night, sweetheart.
- See you in the morning.

32
00:02:49,403 --> 00:02:53,203
- Victor, Illona.
- Bill, Alice.

33
00:02:53,407 --> 00:02:55,899
- Merry Christmas.
- Thank you for coming.

34
00:02:56,343 --> 00:03:00,780
- Thanks so much for coming.
- We wouldn't miss it for the world.

35
00:03:00,981 --> 00:03:04,042
Alice, look at you.
God, you're absolutely stunning!

36
00:03:04,284 --> 00:03:06,318
I don't say that to all the women.
Do I?

37
00:03:06,420 --> 00:03:08,184
- Yes, he does.
- He does?

38
00:03:08,388 --> 00:03:11,358
That osteopath you sent me to,
the guy that worked on my arm?

39
00:03:11,558 --> 00:03:14,994
- You ought to see my serve now.
- He's the top man in New York.

40
00:03:15,195 --> 00:03:17,687
I could have told you that,
looking at his bill.

41
00:03:17,898 --> 00:03:20,299
Go inside, have a drink,
enjoy the party.

42
00:03:20,500 --> 00:03:23,231
I'll see you in a little bit.
Thanks for coming.

43
00:03:36,183 --> 00:03:38,242
Do you know anyone here?

44
00:03:39,553 --> 00:03:42,079
Not a soul.

45
00:03:49,963 --> 00:03:54,366
Why do you think Ziegler invites us
to these things every year?

46
00:03:55,535 --> 00:04:00,029
This is what you get
for making house calls.

47
00:04:11,184 --> 00:04:13,346
You see that guy at the piano?

48
00:04:14,554 --> 00:04:17,046
I went to medical school with him.

49
00:04:17,657 --> 00:04:18,657
Really?

50
00:04:21,962 --> 00:04:24,454
He plays pretty good for a doctor.

51
00:04:25,265 --> 00:04:28,792
He's not a doctor. He dropped out.

52
00:04:31,972 --> 00:04:34,373
Ladies and gentlemen,
I hope you're enjoying yourselves.

53
00:04:34,574 --> 00:04:38,010
The band's going to take a break.
We'll be back in 10 minutes.

54
00:04:38,779 --> 00:04:39,779
Thank you.

55
00:04:46,987 --> 00:04:48,853
Let's go over and say hello.

56
00:04:49,055 --> 00:04:51,456
I desperately need to
go to the bathroom.

57
00:04:51,658 --> 00:04:55,652
You go and say hello,
and I'll meet you where? At the bar?

58
00:04:56,196 --> 00:04:57,254
Good.

59
00:05:07,674 --> 00:05:09,108
Nightingale.

60
00:05:10,010 --> 00:05:11,171
Nick Nightingale!

61
00:05:11,378 --> 00:05:13,608
Oh, my God! Bill.

62
00:05:14,181 --> 00:05:17,116
Bill Harford!
How the hell are you, buddy?

63
00:05:17,317 --> 00:05:20,685
- How long has it been?
- I don't know. 10 years?

64
00:05:20,887 --> 00:05:22,252
And a couple.

65
00:05:22,789 --> 00:05:24,789
- Do you have time for a drink?
- Sure.

66
00:05:28,829 --> 00:05:30,923
You haven't changed a bit.

67
00:05:31,131 --> 00:05:34,032
Thanks, I think.
So how you doing?

68
00:05:34,234 --> 00:05:36,965
Not too bad, you know. Not too bad.

69
00:05:37,170 --> 00:05:39,400
I see you've become a pianist.

70
00:05:39,606 --> 00:05:42,200
Oh, yes, well, my friends call me that.

71
00:05:43,109 --> 00:05:45,669
How about you?
You still in the doctor business?

72
00:05:45,879 --> 00:05:49,873
You know what they say:
"Once a doctor, always a doctor."

73
00:05:50,083 --> 00:05:54,384
Yes, or in my case:
"Never a doctor, never a doctor."

74
00:05:55,255 --> 00:05:57,622
I never did understand
why you walked away.

75
00:05:58,425 --> 00:06:00,757
It's a nice feeling. I do it a lot.

76
00:06:00,961 --> 00:06:02,156
Cheers.

77
00:06:02,762 --> 00:06:06,198
Excuse me.
Nick, I need you a minute.

78
00:06:06,399 --> 00:06:08,026
Be right with you.

79
00:06:08,235 --> 00:06:10,863
I gotta go do something.
If I don't catch you later,

80
00:06:11,071 --> 00:06:14,837
I'll be down at the Village
for two weeks at the Sonata Café.

81
00:06:15,108 --> 00:06:17,770
- Stop by if you get a chance.
- I'll be there.

82
00:06:18,612 --> 00:06:21,582
- It's great seeing you.
- Good seeing you too, man.

83
00:07:03,023 --> 00:07:06,482
I think that's my glass.

84
00:07:06,693 --> 00:07:09,822
I'm absolutely certain of it.

85
00:07:23,810 --> 00:07:27,838
My name is Sandor Szavost.
I'm Hungarian.

86
00:07:38,425 --> 00:07:40,894
My name is Alice Harford.

87
00:07:41,227 --> 00:07:43,286
I'm American.

88
00:07:43,930 --> 00:07:45,830
Delighted to meet you, Alice.

89
00:07:47,434 --> 00:07:52,201
Did you ever read the Latin poet Ovid
on <i>The Art of Love</i>?

90
00:07:54,274 --> 00:07:57,972
Didn't he wind up all by himself...

91
00:07:58,578 --> 00:08:00,945
crying his eyes out

92
00:08:01,147 --> 00:08:04,879
in some place
with a very bad climate?

93
00:08:06,086 --> 00:08:09,021
But he also had a good time first.

94
00:08:09,489 --> 00:08:11,753
A very good time.

95
00:08:14,260 --> 00:08:17,025
Are you here
with anyone tonight, Alice?

96
00:08:20,166 --> 00:08:22,191
With my husband.

97
00:08:22,535 --> 00:08:24,469
Oh, how sad.

98
00:08:25,238 --> 00:08:30,176
But then I'm sure he's the sort of man
who wouldn't mind if we danced.

99
00:08:35,015 --> 00:08:37,143
What do you do, Alice?

100
00:08:37,717 --> 00:08:41,085
Well, at the moment...

101
00:08:41,888 --> 00:08:44,255
I'm looking for a job.

102
00:08:45,458 --> 00:08:49,156
I used to manage
an art gallery in SoHo.

103
00:08:49,896 --> 00:08:52,024
But it went broke.

104
00:08:54,100 --> 00:08:55,590
What a shame.

105
00:08:57,370 --> 00:08:59,839
I have some friends in the art game.

106
00:09:00,573 --> 00:09:02,735
Perhaps I can be of some help.

107
00:09:06,546 --> 00:09:08,173
Thank you.

108
00:09:27,400 --> 00:09:28,959
Someone you know?

109
00:09:32,906 --> 00:09:34,499
My...

110
00:09:35,075 --> 00:09:36,634
husband.

111
00:09:41,314 --> 00:09:44,340
Don't you think
one of the charms of marriage

112
00:09:44,551 --> 00:09:49,250
is that it makes deception
a necessity for both parties?

113
00:09:53,126 --> 00:09:55,754
May I ask why a beautiful woman,

114
00:09:56,262 --> 00:09:59,926
who could have any man in this room,
wants to be married?

115
00:10:02,869 --> 00:10:04,860
Why wouldn't she?

116
00:10:06,673 --> 00:10:08,732
Is it as bad as that?

117
00:10:10,043 --> 00:10:12,410
As good as that.

118
00:10:13,146 --> 00:10:14,944
Do you know Nuala Windsor?

119
00:10:15,148 --> 00:10:19,779
No, and it's very lovely
to meet you both.

120
00:10:21,754 --> 00:10:23,813
How do you spell Nuala?

121
00:10:24,390 --> 00:10:29,328
N-U-A-L-A.

122
00:10:31,131 --> 00:10:33,828
You don't remember me, do you?

123
00:10:35,034 --> 00:10:37,594
You were very kind to me once.

124
00:10:37,804 --> 00:10:41,570
Only once?
That sounds like a terrible oversight!

125
00:10:42,909 --> 00:10:47,142
I was doing a photo session
in Rockefeller Plaza

126
00:10:47,347 --> 00:10:48,940
on a very windy day...?

127
00:10:49,149 --> 00:10:53,347
- And you got something in your eye.
- Just about half of Fifth Avenue.

128
00:10:53,820 --> 00:10:57,313
You were such a gentleman!
You gave me your handkerchief,

129
00:10:57,524 --> 00:10:59,993
which was also clean.

130
00:11:01,661 --> 00:11:05,393
That is the kind of hero
I can be sometimes.

131
00:11:06,366 --> 00:11:09,495
You know why women used to get married,
don't you?

132
00:11:11,004 --> 00:11:13,200
Why don't you tell me?

133
00:11:14,974 --> 00:11:17,944
It was the only way they could
lose their virginity...

134
00:11:18,344 --> 00:11:21,939
and be free to do
what they wanted with other men.

135
00:11:23,016 --> 00:11:25,212
The ones they really wanted.

136
00:11:29,822 --> 00:11:31,813
Fascinating.

137
00:11:35,862 --> 00:11:39,594
Do you know what's so nice
about doctors?

138
00:11:41,167 --> 00:11:44,660
Usually a lot less than people imagine.

139
00:11:46,406 --> 00:11:49,068
They always seem so...

140
00:11:49,943 --> 00:11:51,502
knowledgeable.

141
00:11:52,512 --> 00:11:56,380
Oh, they are very knowledgeable

142
00:11:56,583 --> 00:11:59,416
about all sorts of things.

143
00:12:01,354 --> 00:12:03,516
But I bet they work too hard.

144
00:12:04,057 --> 00:12:07,823
Just think of all they miss.

145
00:12:08,695 --> 00:12:11,096
You're probably right.

146
00:12:12,098 --> 00:12:16,899
Ladies, where exactly are we going?

147
00:12:17,537 --> 00:12:19,096
Exactly?

148
00:12:21,541 --> 00:12:24,033
Where the rainbow ends.

149
00:12:24,677 --> 00:12:26,577
Where the rainbow ends?

150
00:12:26,779 --> 00:12:30,181
Don't you want to go
where the rainbow ends?

151
00:12:30,383 --> 00:12:33,512
Now that depends where that is.

152
00:12:33,720 --> 00:12:35,415
Well, let's find out.

153
00:12:35,622 --> 00:12:38,455
Excuse me, ladies.
Sorry, Dr. Harford.

154
00:12:38,658 --> 00:12:42,959
Could you come with me for a moment?
Something for Mr. Ziegler.

155
00:12:45,298 --> 00:12:46,459
Fine.

156
00:12:48,201 --> 00:12:49,635
To be continued?

157
00:13:12,425 --> 00:13:14,519
Bill, thanks for coming.

158
00:13:16,529 --> 00:13:19,362
We had a little accident here.

159
00:13:19,766 --> 00:13:21,165
What happened?

160
00:13:21,701 --> 00:13:23,635
Well, she was...

161
00:13:24,103 --> 00:13:28,301
she was shooting up,
and she had a bad reaction.

162
00:13:30,076 --> 00:13:31,271
What did she take?

163
00:13:32,412 --> 00:13:35,780
A speedball or a snowball
or whatever the hell they call it.

164
00:13:35,982 --> 00:13:37,848
It's heroin and coke.

165
00:13:40,820 --> 00:13:42,811
Heroin and coke?

166
00:13:45,258 --> 00:13:46,589
Anything else?

167
00:13:48,294 --> 00:13:51,525
We had a couple of drinks,
some champagne. That was it.

168
00:13:52,031 --> 00:13:53,692
How long has she been like this?

169
00:13:54,133 --> 00:13:57,398
Maybe five minutes, six minutes,
something like that.

170
00:13:57,603 --> 00:13:58,729
What's her name?

171
00:14:00,006 --> 00:14:01,064
Mandy.

172
00:14:10,616 --> 00:14:12,516
Can you hear me, Mandy?

173
00:14:13,986 --> 00:14:17,479
Can you hear me?
Move your head if you can hear me.

174
00:14:18,991 --> 00:14:22,086
Move your head if you can
hear me, Mandy. There you go.

175
00:14:22,295 --> 00:14:23,854
You can hear me.

176
00:14:24,063 --> 00:14:28,296
Can you open your eyes for me?
Mandy, can you do that?

177
00:14:29,035 --> 00:14:32,369
Let me see you open your eyes.
There you go, come on.

178
00:14:32,572 --> 00:14:35,507
Come on, look at me. Look at me.

179
00:14:36,109 --> 00:14:38,578
Look at me. Look at me.

180
00:14:39,445 --> 00:14:42,506
Look at me. Look at me, Mandy.

181
00:14:44,217 --> 00:14:45,217
Good.

182
00:14:46,686 --> 00:14:48,051
Good.

183
00:14:49,956 --> 00:14:53,290
I love Victor's art collection,
don't you?

184
00:14:57,230 --> 00:14:59,130
It's wonderful.

185
00:15:00,633 --> 00:15:03,603
Have you ever seen
his sculpture gallery?

186
00:15:07,874 --> 00:15:09,638
I haven't.

187
00:15:10,443 --> 00:15:15,244
He has a wonderful collection
of Renaissance bronzes.

188
00:15:17,417 --> 00:15:19,511
Do you like the period?

189
00:15:22,789 --> 00:15:24,416
I do.

190
00:15:25,091 --> 00:15:27,253
I adore it.

191
00:15:29,328 --> 00:15:31,797
The sculpture gallery is upstairs.

192
00:15:33,232 --> 00:15:35,223
Would you like to see it?

193
00:15:38,304 --> 00:15:40,068
I can show it to you.

194
00:15:43,709 --> 00:15:45,609
We won't be gone long.

195
00:15:53,052 --> 00:15:54,816
Maybe...

196
00:15:57,523 --> 00:16:00,652
not just...

197
00:16:01,828 --> 00:16:03,227
now.

198
00:16:21,280 --> 00:16:25,547
That was really one hell
of a scare you gave us, kiddo.

199
00:16:27,119 --> 00:16:28,450
Sorry.

200
00:16:37,497 --> 00:16:39,556
How are you feeling now, Mandy?

201
00:16:41,601 --> 00:16:42,727
Better.

202
00:16:52,411 --> 00:16:56,871
You are a very, very lucky girl.

203
00:16:58,017 --> 00:16:59,348
You know that?

204
00:17:01,587 --> 00:17:03,214
I know.

205
00:17:04,257 --> 00:17:06,555
You're gonna be okay this time.

206
00:17:07,827 --> 00:17:11,092
But you can't keep doing this.

207
00:17:11,864 --> 00:17:13,332
You understand?

208
00:17:17,770 --> 00:17:21,604
You're going to need some rehab.
You know that, don't you?

209
00:17:23,409 --> 00:17:25,002
I know.

210
00:17:36,355 --> 00:17:37,413
Well, Victor...

211
00:17:39,592 --> 00:17:41,185
I'll leave the rest to you.

212
00:17:41,394 --> 00:17:44,091
Is it okay if I dress her
and get her out of here?

213
00:17:44,297 --> 00:17:48,029
No, I'd keep her here
for another hour.

214
00:17:48,234 --> 00:17:49,724
Another hour?

215
00:17:51,404 --> 00:17:54,533
Then I'd have someone take her home.

216
00:18:00,646 --> 00:18:02,136
Good night, Mandy.

217
00:18:05,051 --> 00:18:07,315
I can't thank you enough for this.

218
00:18:08,020 --> 00:18:10,284
- You saved my ass.
- I'm glad I was here.

219
00:18:10,489 --> 00:18:12,958
Bill. I probably...

220
00:18:13,693 --> 00:18:17,323
I know I don't have to mention this,

221
00:18:17,530 --> 00:18:20,465
but this is just between us.

222
00:18:20,900 --> 00:18:22,197
Of course.

223
00:18:22,702 --> 00:18:23,999
Thanks.

224
00:18:44,991 --> 00:18:49,588
I think I've had
a little too much champagne.

225
00:18:52,732 --> 00:18:56,327
I think I have to go
and find my husband now.

226
00:18:56,535 --> 00:19:01,166
But I'm sure he'll be all right
on his own a little longer.

227
00:19:03,676 --> 00:19:05,075
Yes...

228
00:19:06,479 --> 00:19:08,106
but will I?

229
00:19:08,781 --> 00:19:10,510
Of course you will.

230
00:19:15,655 --> 00:19:19,489
I really have to go.
I have to go.

231
00:19:19,692 --> 00:19:21,456
You don't, you know.

232
00:19:23,162 --> 00:19:25,790
Yes... I do.

233
00:19:31,137 --> 00:19:32,969
I must see you again.

234
00:19:34,774 --> 00:19:37,402
- That's impossible.
- Why?

235
00:19:38,878 --> 00:19:40,676
Because...

236
00:19:43,249 --> 00:19:45,479
I'm married.

237
00:20:50,416 --> 00:20:51,884
Good morning, Lisa.

238
00:20:52,084 --> 00:20:54,178
Good morning, doctor.
Your mail.

239
00:20:54,386 --> 00:20:57,321
Good. Please ask Janelle
to bring me my coffee.

240
00:20:57,523 --> 00:20:59,116
- Sure.
- Thank you.

241
00:20:59,759 --> 00:21:02,729
- Good morning, Sarah.
- Good morning, doctor.

242
00:21:02,928 --> 00:21:05,954
<i>" 'Twas the night before Christmas,
when all through the house,</i>

243
00:21:06,165 --> 00:21:09,032
<i>"not a creature was stirring,
not even a mouse."</i>

244
00:21:13,205 --> 00:21:15,765
Okay. That's fine.
You can put your gown on.

245
00:21:20,513 --> 00:21:22,208
Hold this for Mommy.

246
00:21:23,816 --> 00:21:25,580
Looking forward to Christmas?

247
00:21:26,685 --> 00:21:28,346
Does this hurt?

248
00:21:42,701 --> 00:21:43,930
Right there?

249
00:21:54,947 --> 00:21:56,881
Daddy's gonna like that.

250
00:21:57,550 --> 00:21:59,279
Very good choice.

251
00:22:00,085 --> 00:22:02,417
"...before me...

252
00:22:02,922 --> 00:22:07,860
"when I jump into my bed."

253
00:22:09,895 --> 00:22:14,059
We should call the Zieglers
and thank them for the party.

254
00:22:15,034 --> 00:22:16,866
I've taken care of that.

255
00:22:18,437 --> 00:22:19,871
Good.

256
00:22:20,639 --> 00:22:24,200
So how do you feel about wrapping
the rest of the presents?

257
00:22:25,845 --> 00:22:28,075
Let's do that tomorrow.

258
00:23:14,126 --> 00:23:16,254
Tell me something.

259
00:23:20,966 --> 00:23:24,493
Those two girls...

260
00:23:26,338 --> 00:23:28,966
at the party last night...

261
00:23:34,780 --> 00:23:36,805
Did you...

